      <mj-section background-color="#00a5de">
        <mj-column>
          <mj-text mj-class="white h2" align="center">52% of All JavaScript npm Packages Could Have Been Hacked via Weak Credentials</mj-text>
          <mj-image src="https://www.bleepstatic.com/content/posts/2017/06/27/npm.png"></mj-image>
          <mj-text color="#fff">Tens of thousands of developers using weak credentials to secure their npm accounts inadvertently put more than half of the npm packages (JavaScript libraries and tools) at risk of getting hijacked and used to deploy malicious code to legitimate applications that use them in their build process.</mj-text>
          <mj-text color="#fff">npm Inc, the company that runs the npm package manager, has addressed the issue at the start of June by triggering password reset operations for all affected users.</mj-text>
          <mj-button background-color="#fff" mj-class="blue" href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/52-percent-of-all-javascript-npm-packages-could-have-been-hacked-via-weak-credentials/">
            Read More
          </mj-button>
        </mj-column>
      </mj-section>



      <!-- Pink Articles -->
