          <mj-text mj-class="pink h2">PRMitM: Attackers Can Hide Password Resets Inside Account Registrations</mj-text>
          <mj-image src="https://www.bleepstatic.com/content/posts/2017/06/25/Registration.jpg"></mj-image>
          <mj-text>A research paper published by four Israeli scientists details a new attack called PRMitM, or the "Password Reset Man-in-the-Middle," in which attackers hide password reset interactions for a user's legitimate profile inside account registration interactions on another site.</mj-text>
          <mj-text>The attack falls under the category of social engineering, as it requires an attacker to convince or lure a potential victim to register a profile on a boobytrapped website.</mj-text>
          <mj-button mj-class="bg-pink" href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/prmitm-attackers-can-hide-password-resets-inside-account-registrations/">
            Read More
          </mj-button>
